content.description: Sharp, shallow, sustained finger pods with insecure stemming. What's not to love? Scramble to the top of the pillar below Straight Talk, clip the bolt on your left and set off. You will probably want to place a piece between the 2nd and 3rd bolt to prevent decking on top of the pillar. Grade backs off towards the top 30ish feet when the crack widens to tight hands.
content.protection: 3 bolts protect the first 1/3 of the climb. Gear to 1.5'' for the rest of the climb, with doubles in tips/finger sizes and a few .75s for the top. Also takes small nuts really well.
content.location: In between Lunar Rover and Strait Talk. Start from the top of the pillar below Straight Talk. Bolts are visible from the ground.

content.description: I am going to come out and say that this is one of the best hand cracks around WA. It starts out thin down low and widens to large fists at the top. A nice long route that gave me that great hand crack pump.
content.location: It is the obvious hand crack starting off a pillar ramp.

content.description: To the right of Straight Talk is a shallow corner with reasonable finger locks in either corner. Route is dirty as of May 2020 but once cleaned up a little will be really good. Pro is generally small though it gets quite wide at the top near the anchor, you might regret bringing a BD #4. The start is tricky due to dirt and moss right now but stemming back to the pillar behind you can make things feel more secure. Bolts but no chains at the top. The Tieton River Rock book has this as 10b but it felt very sustained and as hard as Pure Joy at The Bend.
content.protection: Lots of finger sized pieces and a little bit of big gear for the top.
content.location: Right of straight talk and just to the left of yet another tipped pillar look for two cracks which go up past a roof onÂ the left.

content.description:
moonstruck pillar is a pretty fun route consisting of the typical column/arete style climbing found in tieton.  begin up a slightly slabby start for approximately 2 bolts.  as the pillar steepens, better holds slowly present themselves.  fortunately it isn't very pumpy, as sometimes you have to feel around a bit for the holds. the crux felt like it was in the top two bolts, with balancy positioning.

definitely worth doing if you are in the area.
content.protection: approximately 5 bolts.  bolted anchor at the top of the column.
content.location: near the left side of the crag there are two bolted pillars.  this route climbs the right bolted pillar.

content.description: moonstruck is a fun, varied route.  begin in the flare that is immediately right of the right hand bolted column 'moonstruck pillar'.  typical flare action brings you to the top of the little pillar.  from there, finger jams and nice stemming on fun continuous climbing will bring you to the top of the route.  the routes in this area form a sort of ledge made out of columns at the top.  bolt anchors are on top of this ledge.
content.protection: stoppers and cams from fingers to hands.  bolted anchor on top of the column.
content.location: just to the left of the center of moon rocks there are several pillars that lean up against the wall.  the two leftmost pillars have bolted routes.  moonstruck starts just to the right of the right bolted route 'moonstruck pillar', in a bit of a recess that creates a tight flare/dihedral.

content.description:
I am adding this even if I only TR'd it, because it is excellent.

If you are working on 12a trad lines this is great. It would be a tough onsight, I got it clean till the 5.10 R section 2/3- 3/4 way up. There are endless cool moves to good finger locks most of the way.
content.protection: It would be really challenging getting gear in pretty much only finger holds are also only gear spots- maybe slotting in nuts.
content.location:
first thin crack right of Bloody Knuckles, left of Ages of You- 11c -that has 2-3 bolts.

Chain anchor

content.description:
A pretty cool and unusual climb that begins by squeezing through a wide slot and then chimneys up between a large pillar and the main wall. There is a crack for protection and hand holds. When the pillar ends climb about 30 more feet (a bit dirty but seemed pretty solid) to the top of the wall and set a gear belay. Definitely worth doing this route if you are looking for an interesting and adventurous 5.7 to warm up on.

Note: this route is incorrectly labeled as Dirty Thrasher in the picture in the guidebook.
content.protection: Single rack to 2", with a #3 for the anchor at the top (not necessary but nice to have) and a #4 for the start (getting to the wide slot). The crack behind the pillar takes 0.4-0.75, so if I doubled up on anything it would be pieces in this range.
content.location: Look for the wide slot that goes behind a pillar. Just left of where the main trail meets the wall.

content.description:
Climb past some brush in a double OW stem box to a small broken pillar roof. After reaching the roof climb the hand crack right of the roof up to where it widens to full OW range. There is a single bolt inside the top of the OW (unfortunate spot). Top out this pillar, then continue up the hand crack on the right. At the top of the this pillar is a set of anchors straight to your left.

FA Jim Yoder 06'
content.protection: SR to 6". Maybe doubles in BD .75-1
content.location: Right end of Moon Rocks. Two cracks over from Fists and Stuff

content.description: Climb up to and through small roof to a short off width crack (5-6") that narrows hands at break.  climb finishes atop broken column at rap hangers (no chains).
Some dirtiness up to a hand crack roof (dodge the loose block) into knee bars, butterflies and hand/fist stacks. Top out, then climb a techy (and little dirty) crack above with fists to fingers.
content.location: Obvious wide crack above roof with large smear of orange lichen.

climbs.name: Double Crack
climbs.fa: Matt Christensen, Ron Sell, Linda Sell

content.description: Climb up the twin cracks using some good jams. Fun movement.
content.protection:
Standard rack with hand sizes.

There is a fixed sling / locker around the pillar at the top. Use this or walk off to the right.
content.location: Climb the furthest route to the right on the main formation (before the bushes get super dense at the base of the wall). Look for the obvious twin cracks right of the broken tilted pillars (which is a 5.3).

content.description: starts on left side of Blue Moon pillar in a mossy groove, goes to cool chimney till pillar top on right, 10c finger crack on left side of pillar anchor.
content.protection:
No big gear needed for chimney, but the crack opens up inside so be careful how you place the cams. I had a huge hex that I flopped inside hanging at the point where the two columns separate. extra small gear for upper crack, there are some larger cam options up there too- #.75,#1-#2.

Chain anchor.

content.description: Six bolts up the pillar with lots of good footwork and balance required. Really fun route and a great test of how well you and your shoes edge. The first bolt might feel a little high but the crack running up to protects very well if desired. Chains at the top.
content.location: To the immediate left of the large tree bent into a bench is a pillar with 6 shiny bolts running up to the top. This is to the right of the Moon Rise pillar.

content.description:
inside corner on right side of column with bolted 11c- Blue Moon.

Hands- OW- 5.9 to 10a till top of pillar, 10b fingers above using the right side crack.

The OW is grovely as they usually are, but some face holds and inside holds ease the pain.
content.protection: gear rack with extra #.5- .75 for upper crack. #4 or #5 Camalot sizes ok for OW.
content.location: Directly behind the oak tree belay seat. Many anchors above to choose from.
